{"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0,"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[],"toc_visible":true,"authorship_tag":"ABX9TyMtmu2Kla6ud5Ng95YQsFC8"},"kernelspec":{"name":"python3","display_name":"Python 3"},"language_info":{"name":"python"}},"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Support Vector Machine\n","\n","SVM is one of the most popular models in Machine Learning, and it is particularly well suited for classification of complex but small- or medium-sized datasets.\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"cBVud_kHm20D"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 1 Linear SVM Classification\n","\n","In decision tree classifier and logistic regression, we used loss-functions (impurity for decision tree, and cross-entropy for logistic regression) to motivate the algorithms. After we fitted the model, we drew decision boundries that equate predict_probas for different target classes.\n","\n","Can we motive a new algorithm based on the idea of drawing decision boundry? The answer is yes, and the resulting algorithm is SVM. The linear SVM algorithm first hypothesizes the decision boundry as a line $x^Tw+b=0$, then it aims to maximize the distance between the line and the nearest observations, since in general the larger the margin the lower the generalization error of the classifier. In the example graph below, there are two target classes, so the objective is maximize the sum of the two distances.\n","\n","You can think of an SVM classifier as fitting the widest possible street (represented by the parallel dashed lines) between the classes. This is called large margin classification.\n","\n","Notice that adding more training observations “off the street” will not affect the decision boundary at all: it is fully determined (or “supported”) by the observations located on the edge of the street. These observations are called the support vectors (because they are row vectors).\n","\n","![svm](https://editor.analyticsvidhya.com/uploads/729834.png)\n"],"metadata":{"id":"xneSEomq5gcj"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["> Support Vector Machine algorithms are not scale invariant, so it is highly recommended to **scale your data**."],"metadata":{"id":"HJRO3hUxSeUl"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Objective function\n","\n","Now, how should we write the objective function? First we need to formulate the distrance from a point $x_0$ (suport vectors) to the decision boundry $x^Tw+b=0$. This is: $d=\\frac{x_0^Tw+b}{||w||}$, for now we assume that we are anlyzing one side of the street where this distance is positive.\n","\n","We would also like to constraint the point $x_0$ to be on the edge of the street (a.k.a. the *tips* of the support vectors) so that any other points are further to the line. So $\\frac{x_i^Tw+b}{||w||}\\ge d \\space \\forall i$.\n","\n","Note that $w,b$ are not identifiable in the current setup, because we can obtain the same decision boundry by multiplying $w$ and $b$ by a same scalar. Hence, we normalize $x_0^Tw+b=1$ and can then simplify this problem as\n","\n","$$\\min_{w,b} \\frac{1}{2} w^Tw$$\n","$$s.t. \\space y_i(x^t w+b)\\ge 1 \\space \\forall i$$\n","\n","Assume $y_i\\in\\{-1,1\\}$, the constraint addresses the issuse of the sign of the distance.\n","\n","But problems are usually not always perfectly separable with a hyperplane, so we allow some samples to be at a distance from their correct margin boundary. This is called the **soft margin problem**. The penalty term C controls the strength of this penalty, and as a result, acts as an inverse regularization parameter (note that $\\zeta$ and w are negatively related in the constraint, so C is an inverse regularization parameter for $w$). In other words, smaller C value leads to a wider street, more margin violations, and it will generalize better.\n","\n","$$\\min_{w,b}\\frac{1}{2} w^Tw + C\\sum \\zeta_i$$\n","$$s.t. \\space y_i(x^t w+b)\\ge 1-\\zeta_i \\space \\forall i$$\n"],"metadata":{"id":"4DyFWcQ3BJbL"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Or equivalently\n","\n","$$\\min_{w,b}\\frac{1}{2} w^Tw + C\\sum max(0, 1-y_i(w^Tx_i+b))$$\n","\n","where the second part is called the **hinge loss function**\n","\n","![hinge](https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20231109124420/1-(1).png)"],"metadata":{"id":"IYxVYrljzQoX"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Make predictions\n","\n","The linear SVM classifier model predicts the class of a new instance x by simply computing the decision function $w^Tx + b$. If the result is positive,\n","the predicted class ŷ is the positive class (1), or else it is the negative class (-1)."],"metadata":{"id":"GKjiG4T6J4fV"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import numpy as np\n","from sklearn import datasets\n","from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n","from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC\n","from sklearn.inspection import DecisionBoundaryDisplay\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"],"metadata":{"id":"GY6Py1PCySGI"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["iris = datasets.load_iris()\n","X = iris[\"data\"][:,(2,3)] # petal length, petal width\n","y=(iris[\"target\"]==2).astype(np.float64) # Iris-Virginica\n","\n","svm_clf = Pipeline([\n","    (\"scalar\",StandardScaler()),\n","    (\"linear_svc\", LinearSVC(C=1, loss=\"hinge\")) #‘hinge’ is the standard SVM loss # Warning: The strength of the regularization is inversely proportional to C.\n","])\n","\n","svm_clf.fit(X,y)\n","svm_clf.predict([[5.5,1.7]])"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"rpTG0KqEyjia","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772482028939,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":73,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"0aedce59-357d-4144-e93b-bb44182c9a48"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["array([1.])"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":2}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["svm_clf.decision_function([[5.5,1.7]]) # decision function score"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"fIpdRwbWcKxw","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486722393,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":6,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"e5d65337-1d6f-47d9-a714-5bc13eeab4ac"},"execution_count":11,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["array([0.68562445])"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":11}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["svm_clf[1].coef_, svm_clf[1].intercept_ # w and b"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"2cdWxAGhcdWP","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486808975,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":20,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"992f77ed-34f1-403d-d58b-86713e9fbc64"},"execution_count":14,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["(array([[1.63329425, 2.38788235]]), array([-2.50521954]))"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":14}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["svm_clf[1].coef_@svm_clf[0].transform([[5.5,1.7]]).T+svm_clf[1].intercept_ # the definition formula of decision function"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"ZZXSVJICdRY_","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772487099572,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":11,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"b42a908e-9e2a-4683-a35d-195b4e0e7be2"},"execution_count":22,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["array([[0.68562445]])"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":22}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["disp = DecisionBoundaryDisplay.from_estimator(\n","    svm_clf,\n","    X,\n","    response_method=\"predict\",\n","    alpha = 0.1,\n","    xlabel= iris.feature_names[2],\n","    ylabel= iris.feature_names[3],\n",")\n","disp.ax_.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y)\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":455},"id":"iOdSLWsh1XA9","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772482031263,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":249,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"ebd6e0f8-adde-47d2-9df0-f2e413aeb6a3"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["> **The disadvantages of SVM**:\n","\n","- If the number of features is much greater than the number of samples, avoid over-fitting in choosing Kernel functions and regularization term is crucial.\n","\n","- SVMs do not directly provide probability estimates, these are calculated using an expensive five-fold cross-validation (see Scores and probabilities, below)."],"metadata":{"id":"s2zM4woMJ43_"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 2 Nonlinear SVM Classification"],"metadata":{"id":"O6gWKaAE01OD"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Adding transformed features"],"metadata":{"id":"i4gna_XNEo3I"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Although linear SVM classifiers are efficient and work surprisingly well in many\n","cases, many datasets are not even close to being linearly separable.\n","\n","One approach to handling nonlinear datasets is to add more features, such as polynomial features. To implement this idea using Scikit-Learn, you can create a Pipeline containing a PolynomialFeatures transformer (discussed in “Polynomial Regression”), followed by a StandardScaler and a LinearSVC. Let's test this on the moons dataset: this is a toy dataset for binary classification in which the data points are shaped as two interleaving half circles.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"to_ul14S09jV"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.datasets import make_moons\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures\n","\n","X2,y2 = make_moons(noise=1e-1, random_state=1)\n","polynomial_svm_clf = Pipeline([\n","(\"poly_features\", PolynomialFeatures(degree=3)),\n","(\"scaler\", StandardScaler()),\n","(\"svm_clf\", LinearSVC(C=10, loss=\"hinge\"))\n","])\n","polynomial_svm_clf.fit(X2, y2)\n","\n","disp = DecisionBoundaryDisplay.from_estimator(\n","    polynomial_svm_clf,\n","    X2,\n","    response_method=\"predict\",\n","    alpha = 0.1,\n","    xlabel= \"x1\",\n","    ylabel= \"x2\",\n",")\n","disp.ax_.scatter(X2[:, 0], X2[:, 1], c=y2)\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":484},"id":"f22oO4zj4Ao7","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772482324514,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":225,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"97792d86-6bdb-4f70-d606-4bd7136129f1"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stderr","text":["/usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages/sklearn/svm/_base.py:1249: ConvergenceWarning: Liblinear failed to converge, increase the number of iterations.\n","  warnings.warn(\n"]},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["When using SVMs you can also apply an almost miraculous mathematical\n","technique called the **kernel trick**. It makes it possible to get the same result as if you added many polynomial features, even with very highdegree polynomials, without actually having to add them. So there is no combinatorial explosion of the number of features since you don't actually add any features. Let's now take a look at how this trick is applied."],"metadata":{"id":"dTojPKNm5OX9"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Quadratic programming\n","\n","The hard margin and soft margin problems are both convex quadratic optimization\n","problems with linear constraints. Such problems are known as Quadratic Programming (QP) problems. Many off-the-shelf solvers are available to solve QP problems using a variety of techniques that are outside the scope of this note.\n","So one way to train a hard margin linear SVM classifier is just to use an off-the-shelf QP solver by passing it the preceding parameters. However, to use the kernel trick we are going to look at a different constrained optimization problem called the dual problem.\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"P4UIvVs0TmIh"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Dual problem of SVM\n","Given a constrained optimization problem, known as the primal problem, it is possible to express a different but closely related problem, called its dual problem(see [this note](https://www-cs.stanford.edu/people/davidknowles/lagrangian_duality.pdf) for an explanation of duality problem). The solution\n","to the dual problem typically gives a lower bound to the solution of the primal\n","problem, but under some conditions it can even have the same solutions as the primal problem. Luckily, the SVM problem happens to meet these conditions. so you can choose to solve the primal problem or the dual problem; both will have the same solution.\n","\n","The dual problem of the linear SVM objective\n","\n","$$\\min_{\\alpha} \\frac{1}{2}\\sum_{i=1}^n \\sum_{j=1}^n \\alpha_i\\alpha_j y_i y_j \\vec{x_i}^T \\vec{x_j} - \\sum_{i=1}^n \\alpha_i$$\n","$$0\\le\\alpha_i \\le C\\space \\forall i$$\n","\n","Once you find the vector $\\alpha$ that minimizes this equation (using a QP solver), you can compute w and b that minimize the primal problem by using\n","\n","$$\\hat{w} = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\hat{\\alpha}_i y_i \\vec{x_i}$$\n","$$\\hat{b} = \\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i-\\vec{\\hat{w}}^T\\vec{x_i})$$\n","\n","The dual problem is faster to solve than the primal when the number of training\n","instances is smaller than the number of features. More importantly, it makes the kernel trick possible, while the primal does not. So what is this kernel trick anyway?"],"metadata":{"id":"ix7fIJnQ-gtW"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Kernelized SVM\n","Suppose you want to apply a 2nd-degree polynomial transformation (mapping) $\\phi$ to a two dimensional training set, then train a linear SVM classifier on the transformed training set. We can write this quadradic mapping as (don't worry about the $\\sqrt{2}$ coefficient for now, because it is just a scaling factor)\n","\n","$$\\phi (\\vec{x}) = \\phi (x1, x2) = (x_1^2, \\sqrt{2}x_1x_2, x_2^2)$$\n","\n","Notice that the transformed vector is three-dimensional instead of two-dimensional. Now let's look at what happens to a couple of two-dimensional vectors, $\\vec{a}$ and $\\vec{b}$, if we apply this 2nd-degree polynomial mapping and then compute the dot product of the transformed vectors.\n","\n","$$\\phi(\\vec{a})^T\\phi(\\vec{b}) = (a_1^2b_1^2+2a_1b_1a_2b_2+a_2^2b_2^2) = (a_1b_1+a_2b_2)^2 = (\\vec{a}^T\\vec{b})^2$$\n","\n","Now here is the key insight: if you only need dot products in the objective function, there is no need to really transform the feature vector using $\\phi$ and generate a high-dimentional dataset. Instead, you only need to transform the scalar $\\vec{x}_i^T\\vec{x}_j$, i.e. replace the $\\vec{x_i}^T \\vec{x_j}$ in the dual problem by $(\\vec{x_i}^T \\vec{x_j})^2$\n","\n","The function $K(a,b)=(a^Tb)^2$ is called a **2nd-degree polynomial kernel**. Some of the most commonly used kernels are:\n","\n","- d-degree Polynomial: $K(a,b) = (\\gamma a^Tb +r)^d$\n","- Gaussian RBF (Radial basis function): $K(a,b) = exp(-\\gamma||a-b||^2)$\n","- Sigmoid: $K(a,b) = tanh(\\gamma a^Tb+r)$\n","\n","> According to **Mercer's theorem**, if a function K(a, b) respects a few mathematical conditions called Mercer's conditions (K must be continuous, symmetric in its arguments so K(a, b) = K(b, a), etc.), then there exists a function ϕ that maps a and b into another space (possibly with much higher dimensions) such that K(a, b) = ϕ(a)T ϕ(b). So you can use K as a kernel since you know ϕ exists, even if you don't know what ϕ is. In the case of the Gaussian RBF kernel, it can be shown that ϕ actually maps each training instance to an infinite-dimensional space, so it's a good thing you don't need\n","to actually perform the mapping!"],"metadata":{"id":"Kpr_GMi1-iOV"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Make predictions with kernel SVM\n","\n","There is still one loose end we must tie. To go from the dual solution to the primal solution, it seems that we still have ϕ(x(i)) in the function $\\hat{w} = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\hat{\\alpha}_i y_i \\vec{x_i}$. Does it mean that we still need to apply the $\\phi$ transformation? Can you make predictions without knowing w?\n","\n","Well, the good news is \"No\", we don't need w to make predictions. Instead, you can plug in the formula for w into the decision function ${w}^T\\vec{x}+b$. And the resuling formula allows you to apply the kernel trick again.\n","\n","$${w}^T\\vec{x_{new}}+b= (\\sum_{i=1}^n a_i y_i \\phi(x_i))^T\\phi (x_{new}) +b$$"],"metadata":{"id":"g18PSwIDFLRj"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["The kernel trick is implemented by the SVC class. Let’s test it on the moons dataset"],"metadata":{"id":"xzbAybmVHV6X"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.svm import SVC\n","\n","poly_kernel_svm_clf = Pipeline([\n","(\"scaler\", StandardScaler()),\n","(\"svm_clf\", SVC(kernel=\"poly\", degree=3, coef0=1, C=10))\n","])\n","poly_kernel_svm_clf.fit(X2, y2)\n","\n","disp = DecisionBoundaryDisplay.from_estimator(\n","    poly_kernel_svm_clf,\n","    X2,\n","    response_method=\"predict\",\n","    alpha = 0.1,\n","    xlabel= \"x1\",\n","    ylabel= \"x2\",\n",")\n","disp.ax_.scatter(X2[:, 0], X2[:, 1], c=y2)\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":449},"id":"eV6bfzlq5cye","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1708811823304,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":801,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"013b7a6b-d48d-44f3-a489-e8f12becb621"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Let's try the RBF kernel"],"metadata":{"id":"jzWmQ76fH4Lo"}},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"XCXGLvUJm2Ia","colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":449},"executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1708812036149,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":1058,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"911f25f6-1298-414a-a897-08b50e56913f"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"source":["rbf_kernel_svm_clf = Pipeline([\n","(\"scaler\", StandardScaler()),\n","(\"svm_clf\", SVC(kernel=\"rbf\", gamma=5, C=0.01))\n","])\n","rbf_kernel_svm_clf.fit(X2, y2)\n","\n","disp = DecisionBoundaryDisplay.from_estimator(\n","    rbf_kernel_svm_clf,\n","    X2,\n","    response_method=\"predict\",\n","    alpha = 0.1,\n","    xlabel= \"x1\",\n","    ylabel= \"x2\",\n",")\n","disp.ax_.scatter(X2[:, 0], X2[:, 1], c=y2)\n","plt.show()"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 3 SVM Regression\n","\n","The SVM algorithm is quite versatile: not only does it support linear and nonlinear classification, but it also supports linear and nonlinear regression. The trick is to reverse the objective: instead of trying to fit the largest possible street between two classes while limiting margin violations, SVM Regression tries to fit as many instances as possible on the street while limiting margin violations (i.e., instances off the street). The width of the street is controlled by a hyperparameter $epsilon$.\n","\n","You can use Scikit-Learn's LinearSVR class to perform linear SVM Regression. To tackle nonlinear regression tasks, you can use a kernelized SVM model. This can be implemented by the Scikit-Learn's SVR class (which supports the kernel trick).\n"],"metadata":{"id":"GJ0f7IY3I6di"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 4 Multiclass Classification\n","\n","Whereas binary classifiers distinguish between two classes, multiclass classifiers (also called multinomial classifiers) can distinguish between more than two classes.\n","\n","Some algorithms (such as DecisionTreeClassifier or SoftMax) are capable of handling multiple classes directly. Others (such as SVC or Linear classifiers) are strictly binary classifiers. However, there are various strategies that you can use to perform multiclass classification using multiple binary classifiers.\n","\n","For example, one way to create a system that can classify the digit images into 10 classes (from 0 to 9) is to train 10 binary classifiers, one for each digit (a 0-detector, a 1-detector, a 2-detector, and so on). Then when you want to classify an image, you get the decision score from each classifier for that image and you select the class whose classifier outputs the highest decision score or proba. This is called the one-versus-all (**OvA**) strategy (also called one-versus-the-rest).\n","\n","Another strategy is to train a binary classifier for every pair of digits: one to distinguish 0s and 1s, another to distinguish 0s and 2s, another for 1s and 2s, and so on. This is called the one-versus-one (**OvO**) strategy. If there are N classes, you need to train $N × (N – 1) / 2$ classifiers. When you want to classify an image, you have to run the image through all classifiers and see which class wins the most duels. The main advantage of OvO is that each classifier only needs to be trained on the part of the training set for the two classes that it must distinguish.\n","\n","Some algorithms (such as Support Vector Machine classifiers) scale poorly with the size of the training set, so for these algorithms OvO is preferred since it is faster to train many classifiers on small training sets than training few classifiers on large training sets. For most binary classification algorithms, however, OvA is preferred.\n","\n","Fortunately, Scikit-Learn detects when you try to use a binary classification algorithm for a multiclass classification task, and **it automatically runs OvA or OvO**.\n","\n","If you want to force ScikitLearn to use one-versus-one or one-versus-all, you can use the OneVsOneClassifier or OneVsRestClassifier classes. Simply create an instance and pass a binary classifier to its constructor."],"metadata":{"id":"Ows8sC95Tzbr"}}]}